      <Abstract xml:lang="en">Whereas the automatic recognition of image contents is a largely unsolved problem, the amount of electronically available visual data grows every day. Automatic categorization and retrieval of visual data is required to help users trying to find visual information from large image databases. Unfortunately, the limited performance of present-day image recognition techniques forms a major obstacle for the efficient content-based retrieval of visual data from digital sources. The EIDETIC project focuses on the development and study of content-based image retrieval in the context of rapidly growing digital (art) collections in libraries, museums and historical archives. In a review of image retrieval research, Jörgensen (1999) considers classical, concept-based retrieval methods and modern methods such as CBIR. She concludes that we need: "principles derived from the fullest range of applicable disciplines, rather than from isolated or fragmented perspectives. This requires a mechanism to ensure that communication among researchers in different disciplines takes place, in order to provide the broad perspective needed both to define and to solve the problems associated with accessing visual materials" (Jörgensen, 1999). The main thrust of the EIDETIC project is the collaboration of four research groups with expertise in content-based image retrieval (CBIR) and cognitive engineering. During the initial stage of the ToKeN2000 project these groups have exchanged their ideas and shared their resources for studying CBIR (see ToKeN, 2000). It is expected that the continuing synergy of the participating groups the EIDETIC project yields new insights into CBIR research and produces significant improvements in the performance of image retrieval systems. The main research question of the EIDETIC project reads: how can efficient and user-friendly content-based retrieval of visual data be realised? Answering the research question requires both image retrieval techniques and user requirements to be taken into account. Therefore, the proposed research aims at (1) studying and developing content-based image retrieval techniques, and (2) studying the user in interaction with CBIR systems. The basic CBIR techniques to be investigated are: outline-based image retrieval, object-based image retrieval and feature-based image retrieval. Considered in isolation, the three techniques have their specific advantages and disadvantages, but when viewed in combination they may yield an effective solution to the problem of content-based retrieval of images. Machine-learning (ML) algorithms play an important role in the automatic recognition of visual data. ML techniques require well-labelled databases of annotated images and corresponding objects in order to train the algorithms for the task of recognising unknown image material. The Vind(x) system, a prototype developed in the ToKeN2000 pilot project, is an ideal test-bed for collecting labelled objects in images. Retrieval performances will be assessed, using the (to be expanded) digital collection of the Rijksmuseum (i.e., the AdLib and ARIA databases) as a test bench and application domain. In addition, the collection of the "Rijksbureau voor Kunsthistorische Documentatie" and specialised data sets collected by the participants of the EIDETIC project (e.g., a digitised collection of paintings of Vermeer) will be used to evaluate the performance of the techniques for specialist usage. User-centred aspects in CBIR systems such as interface design and user feedback are pivotal for the successful application of the underlying techniques. Therefore, the usability of CBIR systems is assessed for two main types of users: (i) non-experts (e.g., visitors of the Rijksmuseum), and (ii) experts (e.g., art experts studying the visual structure of paintings). In addition, the interest or task of each type of user is taken into account. For instance, experts interested in visual aspects of art objects (e.g., brush, texture, colour, paint) may be distinguished from expert users attributing a historical perspective to art objects (e.g., the role of a depicted person or the meaning of a particular scene). The combined object-based, outline-based and feature-based retrieval techniques will form the core of two main CBIR realisations, i.e., one for each of the two types of users. The main deliverables of EIDETIC are two working systems, one for expert usage and one for non-expert usage. Each system can be tuned to cope with the specific type of task at hand. In addition, scientific papers and Ph.D. theses on the techniques and user-centred aspects of CBIR will be delivered during the course of the project.</Abstract>
